{"key":"processedPost-8524788","value":{"id":8524788,"first":7093376,"last":8524945,"when":1213496395,"utime":"06/15/08 05:19 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />when i had 2 to 2-1/2 inches of substrate all was well, but on this one with 5\" the center is obviously the thickest area of substrate, im wondering if this has anything to do with it</blockquote><br />I've seen several threads here lately where noobs were giving advice to use deep substrates of 5\" and more.&nbsp; Very few trays that deep are going to fruit properly unless you're growing agaricus on composted manure.&nbsp; You can use a thick substrate like that with straw successfully, but not pf cakes.&nbsp; Keep them to 2\" to 2 1/2\".&nbsp; Actually, for best total yield, fruit them as cakes and get several flushes.&nbsp; Cased pf cakes rarely deliver a decent second flush, let alone six to seven flushes you'll get from fruiting them as cakes properly.<br />Don't worry too much about uneven pinsets.&nbsp; With few exceptions, total yield will be similar because fewer mushrooms translates into larger mushrooms.&nbsp; It's still cool to see wall to wall flushes, and it's something to shoot for, but don't sweat it.&nbsp; Patching and careful attention to misting and maintenance is how you get those picture perfect flushes.<br />RR"}}